snippet.textDisplay:
Little description and background of the song/ poetry for those who don't understand Urdu. 

Shikwa means quer/ complaint. In Shikwa, Iqbal expressed his sorrow and complained to ALLAH (SWT) that the Almighty didn't pay back Muslims for believing in him. On the contrary, ALLAH (SWT) blessed others (such as those in the West, Christians and Jews) more than the Muslims even though Muslims fought battles, bore hardships and hunger for Him. In his second poem, Jawab-e-Shikwa (answer to the complaint), Iqbal answered himself to everything he complained about in the Shikwa. He describes that those were the ancestors of today's Muslims who were firm believers of the Almighty and that's why they were successful. Therefore, Muslims of the modern times shouldn't compare themselves with their forefathers. They should rather stop complaining and try to become firm believers like their elders.
